defaultQuestion: defaultWhy is community heating/CHP not more common in the defaultUKdefault?default&#xa0;
defaultResponsedefault: defaultDistrict heating is not more common within the UK for both historical and
default more recent
default reasons.
default Although
default defaultdistrict
default heating has enormous 
defaulteconomic and 
defaultte
defaultchnical potential within the UK, its development within the UK has lagged behind that of Europe. 
defaultDistrict heating has been deployed within the UK since the 
default1950s;
default however its popularity began to wane due to rapidly rising fuel costs in the aftermath of 
defaultthe 1973 oil crisis particularly as most schemes at the time were oil fired.
default 
defaultFurthermore the
default availability
default of 
defaulta 
defaultrelatively cheap
default supply of
default indigenous North Sea 
defaultgas
default, reduced
default the UK’s inclination to focus on increased energy efficiency measures
default,
default such as distr
defaultict heating
default,
default at a time when many European countries with  no such supplies had little
default option but to look at increased energy efficiency
default 
defaultmeasures including district heating.
defaultAdditionally the p
defaultoor manag
defaultement
default and low quality of installation
default of the earlier installed district heating schemes made many 
defaultof them unreliable. In contrast, modern pre-insulated pipes and installation technologies result in networks that are reliable over many decades.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile there is huge potential for greater deploy
defaultment of 
defaultdistrict heating across the UK the relatively small market means 
defaultthat the market for installers remains small and uncompetitive. Added to this is the very high price of installation which makes it hard for many district heating schemes to be financ
defaultially viable.
defaultA sustainable funding mechanism could accelerate the deployment of district heating, making the market more competitive, reducing costs.
default Sustainable funding mechanisms would also achieve more than previous grant funding programmes which were 
defaultinvariably closed part way through the advertised timetable and which led to feast and famine delivery of networks.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UKDEA believes that
default 
defaultsupport could be in the form of a Heat Networks Incentive or a 
defaultloan
default or grant
default mechanism to accelerate the market’s 
defaultdevelopment and
default the
default further expansion of the UK’s district heating networks
default,
default as
default 
defaultoutlined
default in the UKDEA’s 
defaultpolicy proposals 
default to DECC
default in
default 
defaultJuly 2011 and 2012
default (See Appendix
default 2)
default.
default&#xa0;
default In addition to issues related to public funding, the UKDEA believes that the 
defaultprovision of
default policy ce
defaultrtainty for investors in low carbon heat generation could also play a crucial role in providing a stable policy framework and a more enabling environment for further investment in low carbon heat networks. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA further hindrance to the
default wider deployment of district heating schemes has been the effect
defaults
default of current government policy (coupled with austerity) on local authorities. Local authorities often provide leadership and drive in the establishment of heat networks within their respectiv
defaulte 
defaultareas
default and any cuts 
defaultor 
defaultreductions to their functions will 
defaultoften result in the shelving or
default abandoning of planned projects including district heating schemes.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnother
default equally
default important reason why district heating may not be more common in the UK is the per
defaultceived risk involved in making an investment in district heating. D
defaultevelopers and investors may perceive investing in other technologies as relatively less risky by comparison to investing in district heating projects.
default Again the development of a more mature
default market for district heating can help overcome this barrier.
