defaultExecutive SummarydefaultThe UK Government has demonstrated a desire for increased deployment of district energy, which is proven to be an effective way to provide wide areas and diverse c
defaultustomer bases with low carbon energy supplies.  The UK’s current exploitation of district energy is very low compared to our continental neighbours.  However many of the UK’s district energy schemes which are already in operation have clearly demonstrated 
defaultthe substantial benefits that stand to be realise, from reduction of fuel poverty through to greenhouse gas emission savings far in excess of those which can be achieved with the efforts of individual consumers.
defaultDistrict energy networks typically require a
default small number of core loads to get started and then expand in a relatively organic process, picking up consumers within near reach.  In this way, it can take many years for even a modest number of new consumers to connect to any given district energy schem
defaulte.  Servicing wider areas with district energy networks before potential consumers are contracted to connect is simply not possible, due to the small operational margins of the Energy Service Companies (ESCOs) which operate district energy schemes.
defaultThe pro
defaultposed Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator Fund (LCIAF) would operate as a loan fund, enabling pre-servicing of high heat density areas with district energy infrastructure.  This would enable new consumers to be added to district energy networks at a subs
defaulttantially increased rate, helping to decarbonise whole areas of towns and cities.  Repayments towards the loan would be made whenever new consumers connect to the pre-serviced sections of network.  This form of fund is potentially more sustainable than gra
defaultnt funding, as re-payments are re-cycled back into the fund to help incentivise further district energy network installation, maximising the benefits achieved for the given expenditure.
defaultIn addition to accelerating the deployment of low carbon energy across
default the UK, the LCIAF would bring in increased investment from ESCOs, not just towards district energy infrastructure but also for the low carbon energy plant needed to provide these new consumers with energy.
defaultSections 1 to 3 of this paper provide more detail
defaulted background to the current situation and Section 4 proposes a method for the LCIAF to rapidly increase the deployment of low carbon district energy projects throughout the UK.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UK’s District Energy IndustrydefaultThe UK Government’s intentions for increase
defaultd deployment of District Energy seem clear.  In a recent speech to the Royal Geographical Society
default, Chris Huhne called for “more district heating schemes” to help reduce wasted energy.  Greg Barker suggested in a speech to the European Energy Forum in Octo
defaultber
default, that the Green Investment Bank could be used to invest in district heating.  DECC’s own Community Energy Online Portal contains links to a significant volume of information on District Heating.  
defaultHowever, all of this positivity has to be seen in the 
defaultcontext of a significantly under-developed district energy sector in the UK.
defaultCurrent Take-up of District Heating in the United KingdomdefaultP
defaultö
defaultyry’s
default Report to the Department of Energy and Climate Change in April 2009 estimated that district heating “currently provides less than 2% of UK heat demand”
default.  In contrast, use of district heating in continental Europe is far more widespread; the same report i
defaultdentifies that Austria, Finland and Denmark benefit from 18%, 49% and 60% of their total heat supplies, respectively, coming from district heating.
defaultUK District Energy Association SchemesdefaultMembers of the UK District Energy Association have already proved tha
defaultt district energy can play a successful role in mitigating the UK’s greenhouse gas emissions.  District energy schemes operated by UKDEA members deliver over 500 million kWh of heat every year
default, saving approximately 100,000 tonnes of carbon emissions per a
defaultnnum when compared to conventional alternative forms of heat supply.
defaultBeyond the significant carbon emission savings achieved by UKDEA members’ schemes, fuel poverty and constraints on business competitiveness are tackled too.  For example: 
defaultThe UK’s PotentialdefaultThe figures clearly demonstrate that the UK’s district energy potential is not yet being fulfilled.  UK heat sales (including industrial heat use) total 15.7 million MWh
default.  In Germany, sales of heat just from
default district heating schemes (i.e. 
defaultnot
default including industrial heat use) are approximately 74.2 million MWh
default; over four and a half times the UK’s 
defaulttotal
default heat sales.
defaultPöyry’s report demonstrated that the carbon savings achieved by district heating are, on average, 
defaultmuch greater than achieved by stand-alone renewable technologies
default.  With heat responsible for almost half of the UK’s carbon emissions
default, there is no doubt that an increase in delivery of district energy would result in substantial reductions in the UK’s ca
defaultrbon emissions.  
defaultAs stated on the “distributed energy and heat” section of DECC’s website, “a radical shift is needed in how electricity and heat is generated, delivered and used in homes and businesses”
default.
defaultPrevious Support for District EnergydefaultA number of 
defaultfunding schemes have previously been available in the UK to support the development of district energy.  However, whilst the first two funding schemes detailed below have resulted in the development and expansion of district energy in the UK, none of these
default funding mechanisms are available today.
defaultCommunity Energy defaultProgrammedefaultHistorically, this support and grant funding programme has been the most significant funding stream for supporting district energy projects.  The Community Energy Programme (CEP) provided 
defaultgrant capital for installing district heating networks.  This scheme was withdrawn in 2006.
defaultLow Carbon Infrastructure FunddefaultThis initiative was delivered by a partnership of DECC, the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG) and the Homes and 
defaultCommunities Agency (HCA).  This grant funding stream for low carbon community heating schemes is now finished, with all funding committed and no further funding available at present.
defaultRegional Infrastructure FundingdefaultRegional Development Agencies (RDAs) 
defaultoffered this as a potential funding model, whereby European funds were used as loan funding to extend the reach of district energy networks, allowing speculative development of energy networks which could attract consumers at greater rates than the typical
default “organic growth” model of district heating.  Repayments of the loan funding were expected to be made each time a new consumer connected to the district 
defaultenergy network.
default  A UKDEA member explored this potential in considerable detail prior to the recent chan
defaultges to the Regional Development Agencies.
defaultLimitations of the Current Support RegimedefaultDespite DECC’s recognition of the need for a “radical shift” in how energy is delivered, support for district energy is now piecemeal and often short-term.  Mechanisms such
default as Enhanced Capital Allowances, CCL Exemption, Renewable Obligation Certificates and the Renewable Heat Incentive, all help to incentivise various forms of low carbon technology.  However, none of these mechanisms incentivise the district energy networks 
defaultthat could accelerate the deployment of low carbon energy to multiple consumers on an effective, decentralised basis, rather than relying on piecemeal action by individual consumers.
defaultDistrict energy schemes expand through a relatively organic process, conn
defaultecting new developments (and existing buildings at the end of plant-replacement cycles) that are within reach of the existing network.  Costs of new connections can be high, primarily because of the expensive civil works and specialist pipe materials invol
defaultved.  These connections are typically funded by a “capital connection charge”, intended to be no more expensive than the alternative costs of a conventional energy plant solution, so as to incentivise connection.  
defaultOperators of district energy schemes are 
defaultunable to fund speculative pre-servicing of areas themselves, because operational margins are simply not sufficient.  If wider delivery of district energy is to be achieved, a means must be established to accelerate the reach of existing schemes and furthe
defaultr incentivise the commissioning of new ‘core schemes’ with the possibility of rapid expansion to new consumers.
defaultDECC have clearly placed significant emphasis on the drive for community energy.  Without adequate financial support however, community action w
defaultill be stifled and opportunities will be missed.  The long term nature of energy supply and plant replacement cycles means that once a chance of connection to a low carbon energy supply is missed, the opportunity can be wasted for decades to come.  Relying
default on sporadic grant funding schemes results in ‘feast and famine’ delivery, rather than the necessary sustainable growth of district energy networks which can capture opportunities as they arise.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator FunddefaultThis proposed
default ‘Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator Fund’ is based in part around the ‘Regional Infrastructure Fund’ mechanism once put forward by Regional Development Agencies.
defaultAwards from the proposed loan fund would enable district energy schemes to pre-service are
defaultas of high heat density.  Pre-agreed re-payments of the loan are made when new energy consumers connect to these district energy networks, and the re-payments are funded by those consumers’ connection charges.  More effective than grants, this funding mech
defaultanism can be more self-sustaining, recycling the revenues to new schemes and maximising the delivery of low-carbon energy schemes nationwide. 
defaultThis method of funding would also bring increased investment from ESCOs into both district energy networks and al
defaultso the low carbon plant required to provide the substantially increased customer base with energy.  As an example of where increased private sector funding would be brought in by the LCIAF, an ESCO would be able to fund and develop an energy centre on the 
defaultbasis of revenues received from a consumer connecting to the far end of an LCIAF pre-funded network; such a building would not have been able to take part in a district energy scheme in the absence of the LCIAF funded network and the district energy scheme
default would have been smaller or even unviable as a result.  
defaultFigure 
default1
default below illustrates this effect; for this hypothetical development area, the solid red line represents the district energy network that would normally be economically feasible, only supplying the nearest section of development.  The development zone to the 
defaultright of the figure is therefore unable to benefit from low carbon and low cost energy supplies from the district energy scheme and the scheme may be less efficient with the smaller total energy loads.  The dotted red line illustrates a section of LCIAF fu
defaultnded network, picking up all initial phases of development as well as pre-servicing an area for later development phases, thereby maximising take-up of the low carbon district energy solution and allowing an ESCO to invest in developing the most effective 
defaultsolution for these larger energy loads.
defaultFigure 
default1
default - Example of LCIAF extending the reach and effectiveness of a district energy solution
defaultA number of case studies exist which demonstrate both the success of similar funding mechanis
defaultms and where substantial opportunities for development of low carbon energy have been missed, due to lack of available support.  The UKDEA is able to work with DECC in developing policy on a robust evidence-base.
defaultIt’s important to note that additional bene
defaultfits arise from the future-proofing nature of district energy networks; district energy solutions allow even lower-carbon forms of energy generation to be installed in later years, as they become viable, continuing to decarbonise every customer in the year
defaults to come without the need for substantial further effort and investment by those consumers.
defaultProposed MechanismdefaultA more detailed overview of the proposed mechanism is set out below:
defaultRecycling of FundingdefaultRepayments into the fund from consumer connection charges can be recycled out to further low carbon infrastructure projects, making the LCIAF an
default ‘ever-greening’ and more sustainable form of support.  A target long-stop date for the LCIAF could allow further returns 
defaultto the fund to be put towards other areas, once delivery of low carbon infrastructure has been sufficiently accelerated.
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 
default2
default – Example Early Years Delivery of LCIAF
defaultFigure 
default3
default - Illustration of the Low Carbon Infrastructure Fund Mechanism
defaultSources of Funding &amp; Projected BenefitsdefaultAs set out in 
defaultFigure 
default3
default, there are a number of potential sources of funding to support the LCIAF, including the ERDF, General Taxation, JESSCIA funding and payments made as part of zero carbon ‘allowable solutions’.
defaultThe Scottish Government have recently announced a district heating loan fund which should not only incentivise action nationwide but could also provide a useful foundation from which policy makers can proceed and lessons can be learnt
default.
defaultBased on previous 
defaultlevels of funding for district energy, the UKDEA estimate that £50 million pounds is an adequate fund size to incentivise very significant delivery and expansion of district energy, across more than fifty separate areas.  This fund could be fully recovered
default over the long-term, and has the potential to offset in excess of 6 million tonnes of CO
default2
default emissions over the new district energy infrastructure’s lifetime.  Members of the UKDEA are willing to undertake detailed analysis and provide supporting evidence to 
defaultDECC, should this proposal be of interest, to enable a realistic evidence-base to form the basis of policy.  
