defaultExecutive SummarydefaultThe Government has made clear that it plans to increase deployment of district energy in 
defaultthe UK.  This laudable and necessary aspiration needs to be seen in the context of a significantly under-developed district energy sector, compared to its technical potential and the development of district energy in other European Countries where specific
default support mechanisms have been utilised to encourage growth/support networks.
defaultOne of the central aims of the UK District Energy Association is to engage with Government and share the experience of its members, to accelerate the deployment of low-carbon dist
defaultrict energy across the UK.
defaultThe UKDEA is not a trade organisation but instead counts as its Full Members, bodies that are responsible for developing and operating most of the successful district energy schemes in the UK.  Our members include not just privat
defaulte sector energy service companies (ESCOs) but also the public sector authorities who are centrally involved in the development of district energy schemes.
defaultCurrent take up of district energy in the UK is estimated to be less than 2% of heat demand.  In adva
defaultnce of the published results of DECC’s district heating survey, we have undertaken analysis which demonstrates that it should be feasible to supply over 100 TWh of heat (14% of the UK’s heating and hot water demands) through low-carbon district heating net
defaultworks.
defaultAssuming total decarbonisation of these networks in the run-up to 2050, the greenhouse gas emissions savings should exceed over 36 MtCO
default2
defaulte – a 26% reduction in the current greenhouse gas emissions relating to heating and hot water.
defaultThe current energy
default and legislative landscape contains a number of barriers which prevent deployment of district energy, including shortfalls in potential support mechanisms.  District energy often provides the most cost effective means of decarbonising energy supplies on a 
defaultwhole-life cost basis but does suffer from high capital costs.  We have included a basic summary table in this paper of typical district heating costs.  Additionally, we are happy to work with DECC to help develop a more detailed evidence base.
defaultIn Section 
default3, we have proposed a number of distinct policy measures to accelerate the delivery of low-carbon district energy schemes to achieve the realistic but challenging target of delivering within the next 20 years 14% of all heat in the UK from low carbon distr
defaultict energy schemes.  These are summarised below:
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA low carbon heat network incentive of 0.75p/kWh – providing a 
defaultlong-term revenue stream for low carbon heat sales through district energy networks, just as with the RHI.
default&#xa0;
defaultLastly, we have provided two worked examples in Section 4, based on feasibility 
defaultstudies for actual district energy schemes, and how the measures proposed could help to remove the barriers to their delivery.  The case studies demonstrate that these specific policy measures 
defaultwill
default unlock the potential for the rapid expansion of district e
defaultnergy in the UK, as set out in this paper.
